    "## Background\n",
    "\n",
    "One of the primary abstractions used in the Runtime is providing a simple interface by which advanced error supression and mitigation techniques can be leveraged.  Here we will go over the key suppression and mitigation advances in the Runtime.  As we will see, these options are controlled by the `resilience_level` flag that activates more complex mitigation protocals as the level increases."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "efcffd40",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-danger\">\n",
    "   <div>\n",
    "       <big><b>Warning</b></big>\n",
    "   </div>\n",
    "   <br>\n",
    "   Advanced methods such as zero-noise extrapolation and probablistic error cancellation can be assumed to be very much in the beta stage.  Your mileage may vary.\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "058053d2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Frontmatter"
   ]

   "source": [
    "## Error suppression with Runtime\n",
    "\n",
    "One of the simplest things to automate is quantum circuit error suppression.  Error suppression can loosely be defined as any circuit transformation that reduces the possibility of generating errors when the circuit is executed.  Two important examples of this are gate optimization and dynamical decoupling.  \n",
    "\n",
    "Gate optimization is something that every user has already been taking advantage of when using Qiskit.  When mapping circuits to hardware, the Qiskit `transpiler` function automatically applies some amount of gate optimization.  How much optimization is done is controlled by the `optimization_level` keyword argument in `transpile`.  The possible options range from level 0 -> level 3, with level 1 being the default.  In practice, all users should use `optimization_level=3` as it yields the best performance across most families of circuits.\n",
    "\n",
    "In contrast, dynamical decoupling (DD) is error suppression in absence of gates.  Namely, qubits that remain idle for extended periods of time are susceptible to relaxation and dephasing. Dynamical decoupling helps suppress these sources of errors.  \n",
    "\n",
    "The use of error suppression in Runtime is governed by the `optimization_level` argument.  This follows the Qiskit argument of the same name, with the added feature of including DD at `optimization_level=3`.  \n",
    "\n",
    "Although Qiskit itself defaults to `optimization_level=1`, if transpiling the circuits in the Runtime primitives then the default `optimization_level=3`.  There are a host of suppression techniques that are enabled at this level:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 40,
   "id": "2c43908c",
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0f75350a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In addition to this, the circuit is scheduled (timing information added), and a specific DD sequence is added:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c401e757",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![runtime-dd](images/runtime3/runtime-dd.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 41,
   "id": "0eee0541",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def cntrl_hadamard_ladder(N, measurements=False):\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(N)\n",
    "\n",
    "    qc.x(range(N))\n",
    "    qc.h(range(N))\n",
    "\n",
    "    for kk in range(N // 2, 0, -1):\n",
    "        qc.ch(kk, kk - 1)\n",
    "    for kk in range(N // 2, N - 1):\n",
    "        qc.ch(kk, kk + 1)\n",
    "    if measurements:\n",
    "        qc.measure_all()\n",
    "    return qc"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "52c56469",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us make a 12Q version of our ladder and the usual $\\langle Z^{\\otimes N}\\rangle$ expectation value operator and run using `optimization_level=0` and `optimization_level=3`.  We also need to make sure to turn off the default mitigation (which we will get to in the next section) by setting `resilience_level=0`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 42,
   "id": "0badc176",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "N = 12\n",
    "qc = cntrl_hadamard_ladder(N)\n",
    "oper = SparsePauliOp.from_list([('Z'* N, 1)])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d3dd1f6b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Run our two jobs in a session:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 43,
   "id": "0f2ad5ae",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "suppresion_jobs = []\n",
    "with Session(backend=backend):\n",
    "    estimator = Estimator()\n",
    "    suppresion_jobs.append(estimator.run(qc, oper, shots=1e4, optimization_level=0,\n",
    "                                         resilience_level=0))\n",
    "    suppresion_jobs.append(estimator.run(qc, oper, shots=1e4, optimization_level=3,\n",
    "                                         resilience_level=0))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0d0b94ec",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Grab the resulting expectation values"
   ]

While in both cases we are nowhere close to the desired answer, the answer at `optimization_level=0` really highlights the need for error suppression techniques like advanced gate optimization methods, better qubit routing, and error aware qubit selection; all of which are enabled by default in the Runtime.\n",
    "\n",
    "Other important information is returned in the `metadata` of the result:"

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "56f4920a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Error mitigation in Runtimes\n",
    "\n",
    "While error suppression tries to prevent errors from occuring in the first place, error mitigation attempts to deal with those errors that do occur.   There are two basic types of error mitigation, those that correct measurement errors, and those that correct for gate errors.  Some methods can combine both.  The table below summarizes what mitigation technics are enabled at each `resilience_level` setting:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "54fc0328",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "| Resilience setting | Sampler | Estimator |\n",
    "| --- | --- | --- |\n",
    "| **Level 0** | No mitigation | No mitigation | \n",
    "| **Level 1** (default) | M3 readout correction | TREX readout correction | \n",
    "| **Level 2** | No mitigation | ZNE (no readout correction) | \n",
    "| **Level 3** | No mitigation | PEC | "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "47b68e1c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Level 1\n",
    "\n",
    "The default level 1 setting turns on readout error mitigation for both the `Sampler` and `Estimator`.  However, two different methods are used to perform this mitigation.  First, the `Sampler` uses the [matrix-free measurement mitigation (M3) method](https://doi.org/10.1103/PRXQuantum.2.040326) that computes a quasi-distribution of corrected values in a truncated probability space.  The `Estimator` instead uses the [twirled-readout mitigation (TREX) method](https://arxiv.org/abs/2012.09738), which does not produce an output probability distribution, but is useful for mitigating expectation values.  In both cases there is a price to pay in terms of an increased variance in the output.  This increase can be quantified in terms of an \"overhead\" that is the factor of additional shots that needs to be taken to recover the variance of the unmitigated output.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let us turn on `resilience_level=1` (along with using the default optimization level) and see what we get:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 48,
   "id": "35e359e1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "with Session(backend=backend):\n",
    "    estimator = Estimator()\n",
    "    sampler = Sampler()\n",
    "    # We are going to be explicit and set resilience_level=1 even though it is default\n",
    "    mitigation_expval_res = estimator.run(qc, oper, shots=1e4, resilience_level=1).result()\n",
    "    mitigation_quasi_res = sampler.run(qc.measure_all(inplace=False), shots=1e4, resilience_level=1).result()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "17c762eb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The `Estimator` result comes back much better:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 49,
   "id": "83d45373",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "16ef84bf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So we that `resilience_level=1` does a much better job than before; an indication that short-depth circuits like the one used here are heavily affected by readout errors.  The remaining loss of accuracy is primary related to gate errors, and requires additional mitigation.\n",
    "\n",
    "As already mentioned, there is a price to pay when performing mitigation that shows up as an increase in the variance of the resulting expectation values:"

    "metadata"

    "print('Standard deviation:', np.sqrt(metadata['variance']/metadata['shots']))"
   ]
  },

   "id": "b060f3b7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Comparing to our previous answer with `resilience_level=0`, the variance has gone up by a factor of ~5 here.  This means that more shots must be taken if one wants to get a mitigated expectation value with the same precision as the unmitigated value."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ab927953",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Using the `Sampler` to compute the same expectation value also results in improvement:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "048ff69d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The metadata from the `Sampler` is not the same as the `Estimator`.  Rather it returns `readout_mitigation_overhead` that is the increase in the number of shots that needs to be taken to get back to the same variance as the unmitigated case.  It is very much circuit and device specific; the better the device, the lower this value is.  Additionally, the time it took to do the mitigation is given."
   ]
  },
  {

   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c1917051",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Level 2\n",
    "\n",
    "Resilience levels 2 & 3 are designed for the `Estimator` only as the mitigation methods used at these levels are targetting expectation values.  At `resilience_level=2` the `Estimator` performs zero-noise extrapolation (ZNE) in an effort to extract a (possibly biased) estimate of the requested expectation values at zero noise.  ZNE works by running \"stretched\" circuits where the goal of the stretching is to increase the gate noise in the circuit and compute expectation values at these various noise levels.  Then, one can in-principle extrapolate back to the zero-noise limit and get a mitigated value.\n",
    "\n",
    "There are two ways to stretch circuits, each with its pros and cons:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e37aa96a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![analog-zne](images/runtime3/analog_zne.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0c187f31",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![digital-zne](images/runtime3/digital_zne.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "79cea285",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Each method has its pros and cons:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Analog stretching\n",
    "    - Formally correct method\n",
    "    - Can stretch to arbitrary scaling factors\n",
    "    - Requires calibration of gates for all sretch factors\n",
    "    - Choosing stretch factors is tricky\n",
    "    - Harder to impliment without direct hardware access\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Digital stretching\n",
    "    - Much easier to implement\n",
    "    - Not directly the same as analog stretch\n",
    "    - No additional calibrations required\n",
    "    - Stuck with stretch factors of 1,3,5,...\n",
    "    - Can easily hit T1 limit on deeper circuits\n",
    "    \n",
    "Because of ease of implementation, the digital version is what is used in the `Estimator` and `resilience_level=2`.  Lets try it out:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 56,
   "id": "a429d370",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "with Session(backend=backend):\n",
    "    estimator = Estimator()\n",
    "    # Turn on resilience_level=2 for ZNE\n",
    "    zne_res = estimator.run(qc, oper, shots=int(1e4), resilience_level=2).result()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6a57557b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Lets look at the resultant expectation value:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 57,
   "id": "d320f899",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "0.2325333333333334"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 57,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "zne_res.values[0]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "88e725ff",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see that, while there is some improvement, the answer did not change appreciably from the unmitigated value we had before:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 58,
   "id": "3fc6d620",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "0.1942"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 58,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "suppression_res[1]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b90be75a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The reason for this is that, at present, `resilience_level=2` does not perform readout mitigation.  Thus short-depth circuits like we have here have expectation values heavily affected by readout errors.  Because ZNE is attempting to correct for gate errors only, the presence of readout errors greatly affects the expectation values used at each stretch level, giving a different extrapolation.  As such, until readout mitigation is turned on with ZNE, benefits from this method are limited, and only deeper circuits are likely to see an improvement."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "33978861",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There is also quite a bit of metadata associated with a ZNE execution:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 59,
   "id": "1be46275",
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": true
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{'zne': {'noise_amplification': {'noise_amplifier': \"<TwoQubitAmplifier:{'noise_factor_relative_tolerance': 0.01, 'random_seed': None, 'sub_folding_option': 'from_first'}>\",\n",
       "   'noise_factors': [1, 3, 5],\n",
       "   'values': [0.2044, 0.1428, 0.0876],\n",
       "   'variance': [0.95822064, 0.97960816, 0.99232624],\n",
       "   'shots': [10000, 10000, 10000]},\n",
       "  'extrapolation': {'extrapolator': 'LinearExtrapolator'}}}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 59,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "zne_res.metadata[0]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b1928ed7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "showing how the ZNE runs were configured, the expectation values obteind from the `noise_factors` (stretch factors), and the type of extrapolation used.  Many of these options are configurable, but require deeper understanding than we can give here."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "15fc65e7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-warning\">\n",
    "   <div>\n",
    "       <big><b>Important</b></big>\n",
    "   </div>\n",
    "   <br>\n",
    "   Using ZNE effectively is still very much a trial and error process, and pure automation of the method is still a research question.  Additionally, there are strict requirements on error rates that need to be statisfied in order for the method to be effective at large numbers of qubits.  To do so nominally requires additional suppression methods, E.g. see: <a>https://arxiv.org/abs/2108.09197</a>\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "908d234c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Level 3\n",
    "\n",
    "<div class=\"alert alert-danger\">\n",
    "   <div>\n",
    "       <big><b>Warning</b></big>\n",
    "   </div>\n",
    "   <br>\n",
    "   Activating resilience level 3 should only be done with caution, and the knowledge that it can easily result in a time-out of your estimator job that has a 4 hour max. limit, or that it may not work as intended.\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "Level 3 turns on probabilistic error cancellation (PEC), which is by far the most powerful (and expensive!) mitigation protocal.  In short, it is capable of, on average, mitigating expectation values for both gate and measurement noise.  This of course comes at a cost which is exponential in both the number of qubits and number of entangling gate layers in a circuit. The base of this exponential is determined by device quality, and therefore this overhead is exponentially reduced as device metrics such as two-qubit gate error rates improve."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e0105d55",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![pec1](images/runtime3/pec1.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "43b8701a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![pec2](images/runtime3/pec2.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "29a99c7d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To date, there is no IBM Quantum processor that can perform PEC on anything more than trivial circuits without timing out.  Runtimes of even the most basic of circuits have execution times of an hour or more.  Therefore, here we demonstrate this method using a simple 4Q GHZ state, where the algorithm has to learn only two unique layers."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 126,
   "id": "66960451",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 598.479x325.08 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 126,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 259,
       "width": 466
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ghz = QuantumCircuit(4)\n",
    "ghz.h(2)\n",
    "ghz.cx(2,1)\n",
    "ghz.cx(2,3)\n",
    "ghz.cx(1,0)\n",
    "ghz.measure_all()\n",
    "ghz.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "09c40dc5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us build the usual $\\langle Z^{\\otimes N}\\rangle$ operator that, for even values of $N$ has an ideal expectation value of `1.0`"

    "## Hands-on example: Wormhole via runtime\n",
    "\n",
    "Our example for showing the power of DD on today's quantum systems comes courtesy of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory (LBNL) in the form of wormhole inspired teleportation:\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Towards Quantum Gravity in the Lab on Quantum Processors** \\\n",
    "  Illya Shapoval, Vincent Paul Su, Wibe de Jong, Miro Urbanek, Brian Swingle \\\n",
    "  [arXiv:2205.14081](https://arxiv.org/abs/2205.14081)\n",
    "  \n",
    "The basic idea behind this work can be seen from Fig.(1) of their paper:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7cae2cfe",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![wormhole](images/runtime3/wormhole.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0a2823f8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We want to see how the teleportation protocall behaves as we vary the coupling strength $g$ by evaluating the expectation value $\\langle Z\\rangle$ of the state at the end.  To this end, we create a quantum circuit parameterized by a single variable $g$:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 60,
   "id": "5ff6e852",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

   ]
  },

    "qc.rzz(g, 2, 3)\n",

   "source": [
    "To understand the range of values over which to vary $g$ let us look at the results from the paper given by Fig.~(5):\n",
    "\n",
    "![results](images/runtime3/results.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7bffba80",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see that rescaled variable $g/2\\pi$ is varied over the range $[0, 0.5]$, with the largest signal at $g/2\\pi = 0.25$.  Lets try to first repoduce the ideal result and then do a noisy (not scheduled) simulation for a target system.\n",
    "\n",
    "To make life easy, lets choose just a few points:\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "g_vals = np.linspace(0, np.pi, 11)\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 79,

   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],

    "num_phases = 11\n",
    "\n",
    "g_vals = np.linspace(0, np.pi, num_phases)\n",
    "\n",
    "ideal_circs = [qc.assign_parameters([val]) for val in g_vals]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d8f802f0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Lets look at the difference when using `backend.run()` and the `Estimator` runtime.  Moreoever, lets look at various combinations of `optimization_level` and `resilience_level` for the runtime:\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "optimization_level=2, resilience_level=0\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "optimization_level=3, resilience_level=0\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "optimization_level=3, resilience_level=1\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "In this example, the qubit we want to measure is Q5 (this will be important)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7f393d3a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Ideal results"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3775f6ad",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   ]

   ]
  },

  },

   ]

   "cell_type": "code",

   ]

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 85,
   "id": "f25b0890",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "raw_result = [sampled_expectation_value(cnts, wormhole_oper) for cnts in raw_counts]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2d0a2f74",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Estimator on real-hardware"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 87,
   "id": "848777de",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "wormhole_jobs = []\n",
    "session = Session(backend=backend)\n",
    "estimator = Estimator(session=session)\n",
    "\n",
    "wormhole_jobs.append(estimator.run(ideal_circs, [wormhole_oper]*num_phases,\n",
    "                                   shots=1e4, \n",
    "                                   optimization_level=3,\n",
    "                                   resilience_level=0))\n",
    "\n",
    "wormhole_jobs.append(estimator.run(ideal_circs, [wormhole_oper]*num_phases, \n",
    "                                   shots=1e4, \n",
    "                                   optimization_level=3,\n",
    "                                   resilience_level=1))"
   ]
  },

    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "ax.plot(g_vals/(2*np.pi), ideal_result, 'o--', ms=10, lw=1, label='Ideal')\n",
    "ax.plot(g_vals/(2*np.pi), raw_result, 'o--', ms=10, lw=1, label='Raw')\n",
    "ax.plot(g_vals/(2*np.pi), wormhole_results[0], 'o--', ms=10, lw=1, label='-O3 -R0')\n",
    "ax.plot(g_vals/(2*np.pi), wormhole_results[1], 'o--', ms=10, lw=1, label='-O3 -R1')\n",
    "ax.legend()\n",
    "ax.set_ylim([-1.1, 0.1])\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('$g/2\\pi$');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c9dc1618",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see that the raw results produced with `backend.run()` show absolutely no signal, whereas the results from the Runtime show an improved outcome.  This is because of the dynamical-decoupling sequences inserted by the runtime transpiler.  In this casem, that addition means the difference between a signal and pure noise.  Adding measurement mitigation at `resilience_level=1` does not seem to have helped here.  This is a bit surprising, as we are only measuring a single-qubit; the mitigation procedure should be trivial."
   ]
